## Theory

### What is SSH?

**SSH (Secure Shell Protocol)** lets you remotely connect to another machine over a network — securely. The "secure" part matters: all communication between your machine and the server is encrypted, so no one intercepting the traffic can read it.

SSH is one of the most common tools in any Linux/security workflow. It was assigned its own standard port: **Port 22**.

### What is a Port?

Think of a server as an office building. The IP address gets you to the right building, but the **port number** tells you which room (service) you need. Port 22 is the default room for SSH. Since this game runs SSH on port `2220` instead, you need to explicitly tell your SSH client which port to use.

### How to Use SSH

**On Linux/macOS:** Use the terminal directly with the `ssh` command.  
**On Windows:** Use a terminal (Windows 11 has one built-in) or a tool like [PuTTY](https://www.putty.org/) if you're on an older version.

Want to explore SSH further? Run:
```bash
man ssh
```
This opens the full manual for the `ssh` command — a habit worth building for any Linux tool you use.

