## Solution

### Step 1 — Build the SSH Command

The basic structure for connecting with SSH is:

```bash
ssh <username>@<host> -p <port>
```

Replace the placeholders with the values from the task:

```bash
ssh bandit0@bandit.labs.overthewire.org -p 2220
```

> The `-p 2220` flag is required here because the server isn't using the default port 22. Without it, the connection will be refused.

---

### Step 2 — Run the Command and Enter the Password

Run the command in your terminal. You'll first see a prompt asking for the password:

```
bandit0@bandit.labs.overthewire.org's password:
```

Type `bandit0` and press **Enter**.

>  On Linux/macOS, nothing will appear as you type the password — no dots, no asterisks. That's normal behavior. Just type it and hit Enter.

---

